# tl;dr

Cast `Object` object to `Integer` object. Then let auto-boxing implicitly change `Integer` object to `int` primitive. 

    int d = ( Integer ) vector.get(i);  // Cast `Object` to `Integer`, then implicit auto-boxing to `int`. 

Even better, revise your code:

```java
SequencedCollection &lt; Integer &gt; inputs = List.of ( 1 , 2 , 5 , 6 );
for ( Integer input : inputs )
{
    if ( input % 2 != 0 )
    {
        System.out.println ( input );  // Print odd numbers.
    }
}
```

## Auto-boxing

You said:

&gt;I tried using cast e.i. (int)

Collections such as `Vector` hold objects, not primitives. When you add a primitive literal such as `1` or `5` to such a collection, Java automatically converts these `int` values into objects of the wrapper class `Integer`. This conversion is known as [auto-boxing][1]. 

In other words, your code:

    vector.add(2);

… is equivalent to a call to [`Integer.valueOf`][2], returning a `Integer` object:

    vector.add( Integer.valueOf( 1 ) );  // Making an `Integer` object from a primitive `int`. 

Your call `vector.get(i)` returns an object, not a primitive. So your cast `(int)` makes no sense. Casting does not work across the chasm between primitives and objects. Crossing that chasm is the work of boxing. 

## Cast

As discussed above, you actually put `Integer` objects into your `Vector`. But you declared the `Vector` as holding objects of the superclass [`Object`][3]. When retrieving, you get `Object` objects rather than `Integer` objects. 

You must cast from `Object` to the concrete class `Integer`. 

    Integer d = (Integer) vector.get(i) ;

As discussed above, this cast `(Integer)` is *not* the same as your cast attempt `(int)`. 

## Declare specific type

But this is a fix to your less than optimal code. If your collection holds `Integer` objects, say so. 

You need not repeat the `Integer` type on the right side of the assignment; the compiler can infer that fact from the left side.

    Vector &lt; Integer &gt; vector = new Vector &lt;&gt; ( );

After specifying the more concrete type, we no longer need that cast.

    Integer d = inputs.get ( i );  // Retrieving an `Integer` object from a known list of `Integer` objects. So no cast needed.

## Avoid `Vector` class

Another problem: [`Vector`][4] is an old class from the earliest versions of Java, before the [Java Collections Framework][5] was built. That class is now legacy, as noted in its Javadoc. 

## `SequencedCollection` &amp; `ArrayList`

Instead, use a [`SequencedCollection`][6] implementation such as [`ArrayList`][7].

By the way, use more descriptive names for your variables. Good names makes your code easier to read and more [self-documenting][8]. So something like `inputs` rather than `vector`. 

    SequencedCollection &lt; Integer &gt; inputs = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;() ;

## `List.of` 

Rather than call `add` multiple times, use the [`List.of`][9] feature for more compact code.

    SequencedCollection &lt; Integer &gt; inputs = List.of ( 1 , 2 , 5 , 6 );

The `List` object returned by `List.of` is [unmodifiable][10], not allowing additions or deletions. That works in your situation. 

## Enhanced `for` loop

To simply loop through a collection, you can use the enhanced `for` loop.

    for ( Integer input : inputs )

So now our code looks like this:

```java
package work.basil.example;

import java.util.List;
import java.util.SequencedCollection;

public class Nums
{
    public static void main ( String[] args )
    {
        SequencedCollection &lt; Integer &gt; inputs = List.of ( 1 , 2 , 5 , 6 );
        System.out.println ( &quot;Inputs: &quot; + inputs );
        for ( Integer input : inputs )
        {
            if ( input % 2 == 0 )
            {
                System.out.println ( input );
            }
        }
    }
}
