items.body_markdown:
In Java, arrays don&#39;t override `toString()`, so if you try to print one directly, you get the `className` + &#39;@&#39; + the hex of the [`hashCode`][1] of the array, as defined by `Object.toString()`:

```java
int[] intArray = new int[] {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
System.out.println(intArray); // Prints something like &#39;[I@3343c8b3&#39;
```

But usually, we&#39;d actually want something more like `[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]`. What&#39;s the simplest way of doing that? Here are some example inputs and outputs:

```java
// Array of primitives:
int[] intArray = new int[] {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
// Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

// Array of object references:
String[] strArray = new String[] {&quot;John&quot;, &quot;Mary&quot;, &quot;Bob&quot;};
// Output: [John, Mary, Bob]
```

  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Java_hashCode()
